<article>
    <h1>Worst and best bets</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200906/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-06"><time>2020-09-06</time></a>
        - <span>INVEST</span>
        - <span role="byline">Choo Yun Ting</span>
    </section>

    <p>Q What has been your big­gest in­vest­ment mis­take?</p>
    <p>A Think­ing short term and try­ing to an­tic­i­pate the pub­lic mar­kets. They’ve con­sis­tently taught me that it’s not a game that I’m good at.</p>
    <p>When you deal in an illiq­uid as­set class, the pub­lic mar­kets ap­pear great, since there is liq­uid­ity, mar­ket in­sights and full trans­parency of data, but the trade-off is volatil­ity.</p>
    <p>Mar­kets can turn at any time, so un­less you’re play­ing a long game, it can be­come too stress­ful.</p>
    <p>Q And your best in­vest­ment?</p>
    <p>A My best in­vest­ments have all been with Jun­gle Ven­tures. At our firm, we have a great team ap­proach and lever­age the cog­ni­tive di­ver­sity of the group, which has al­lowed us to make some very good de­ci­sions.</p>
    <p>It’s hard de­cid­ing when to in­vest and when to pass, es­pe­cially when we are see­ing thou­sands of op­por­tu­ni­ties each year, but mak­ing only five or six new in­vest­ments each year. It takes a great deal of rigour.</p>
    <p>Jun­gle Ven­tures has had al­most one exit ev­ery year since its in­cep­tion 10 years ago. Among its re­cent ex­its are lo­cal in­ven­tory and or­der man­age­ment soft­ware plat­form In­tuit last month, fin­tech lender Pay Sense in Jan­uary, and Sin­ga­pore-head­quar­tered health tech start-up Klin­ify, which was ac­quired by Zuel­lig Pharma last year.</p>


